## Minimum Source Depth

Target at least 100 pages, or equivalent depth, of disease-specific material
before considering the chapter mature.

Equivalent depth may include:

- textbook chapters
- professional guidelines or appropriateness criteria
- radiology teaching modules
- review articles or consensus papers
- selected primary research for narrow technical claims

Record the approximate source depth and what was actually read. Do not mark a
chapter mature if the source review is mostly abstracts, snippets, patient
education pages, or generic web summaries.

## Minimum Image Review Depth

For imaging-heavy chapters, target at least 50 reviewed image candidates before
considering figure evidence mature.

Image candidates may include locally saved figures, link-only figures,
teaching-file examples, source-page image sets, and comparator or mimic images.
For each candidate, record:

- source URL
- figure URL or source-page anchor when available
- figure label or source-local identifier
- what the image appears to show
- what the source says it shows
- reuse status
- whether it was saved locally, linked only, rejected, or deferred
- which disease chapter sections it supports

Save images locally only when reuse terms explicitly permit it. If rights are
unclear, record the figure as link-only and keep searching.

## Source Selection Principle

Use authoritative, relevant sources that match the breadth of the claim.

For broad disease claims, search broad clinical sources first: medical imaging
textbooks, textbook-style clinical references, clinical guidelines,
professional criteria, radiology training material, broad review articles, and
broad consensus papers.

Useful places to look include:

1. Medical imaging textbooks or textbook-style chapters available on the web,
   such as NCBI Bookshelf chapters or open educational radiology texts.
2. Professional society guidance and appropriateness criteria, such as ACR,
   RSNA, ASNR, AAN, ILAE, NICE, or disease-specific society guidance.
3. Authoritative radiology training resources written for clinicians,
   radiologists, or trainees, such as Radiology Assistant, MRI Online/Medality,
   Radiopaedia reference articles with citations and revision history, or
   accredited professional education material.

For narrow claims, use narrow sources: primary studies or focused papers about a
specific imaging biomarker, radiomics method, pathology correlation, unusual
subtype, small cohort, segmentation method, or statistical-performance result.

Do not build a general disease chapter by stitching together a scattered set of
narrow papers. When a source supports only a narrow claim, label the claim as
narrow. Avoid patient-facing health pages, SEO summaries, unsourced blog posts,
and general consumer explanations as sources for clinical claims.

## Source Archive And Local Cache

Record source URLs and local cache status in a disease-specific source evidence
record when source material is downloaded for reproducibility.

Recommended source evidence path:

```text
docs/clinical-statistical-expert/diseases/<disease>.sources.json
```

Recommended source evidence schema:

```text
skillforge/templates/clinical-statistical-expert/disease.sources.schema.json
```

Recommended local cache path:

```text
.skillforge/source-cache/clinical-statistical-expert/<disease>/<date>/
```

The local cache is ignored by git and is for updating the disease chapter on
the current machine. Do not commit full source pages, PDFs, article HTML, or
training pages unless redistribution is explicitly permitted and recorded. For
public repo artifacts, commit source URLs, citation metadata, supported claims,
cache status, date accessed, checksums when cached, and reuse notes.

Mark source cache status explicitly:

- `cached-local-only`
- `cached-local-only-and-figure-saved-in-repo`
- `downloaded-but-needs-review`
- `downloaded-but-client-challenge`
- `download-failed`
- `url-only`

Downloaded files that are access-denial pages, client challenges, login pages,
or incomplete landing pages must not be treated as source evidence.

Use the helper when creating source metadata or local cache entries:

```text
python -m skillforge source-archive <disease> --source-id <id> --title "<title>" --url <url> --source-type "<type>" --claim-breadth "<broad/narrow/scope>" --section "<Disease.md section>" --download --json
```

Omit `--download` when recording a URL-only source that should not be cached
locally.

## Search Strategy

Use combinations of:

- disease name and aliases
- modality terms: MRI, CT, PET, SPECT, EEG, pathology, angiography
- sequence terms: T1, T2, FLAIR, DWI, ADC, SWI, GRE, contrast, perfusion,
  spectroscopy
- clinical-course terms: natural history, disease course, progression,
  recurrence, relapse, chronic, stable, treatment response, resolution,
  follow-up, serial imaging
- structural terms: cortical, subcortical, periventricular, deep white matter,
  corpus callosum, basal ganglia, thalamus, brainstem, cerebellum,
  hippocampus, postoperative, posttreatment
- mimic terms: differential diagnosis, mimic, pseudoprogression, treatment
  effect, demyelination, infarct, tumor, infection, inflammation, radiation
  necrosis
- statistical terms: endpoint, biomarker, inter-reader variability,
  misclassification, cohort definition, adjudication, longitudinal model,
  sensitivity analysis

Example searches:

```text
<disease> brain MRI textbook review
<disease> clinical guideline imaging MRI
<disease> radiology teaching MRI
<disease> MRI natural history progression follow-up
<disease> MRI differential diagnosis mimic
<disease> ACR appropriateness criteria MRI
<disease> imaging biomarker endpoint cohort definition
```

